The Laplace transform of a signal \(x(t)\) multiplied by a rectangular pulse from 0 to 1 is computed by integrating the product of the signal and the exponential \(e^{-st}\) over the interval [0, 1]. We split the integral into two parts and compute each separately: 1. The first integral: \[ \int_{0}^{1} e^{-t} e^{-st} \, dt = \int_{0}^{1} e^{-(s + 1)t} \, dt \] Evaluating this integral, we get: \[ \left[ \frac{e^{-(s + 1)t}}{-(s + 1)} \right]_{0}^{1} = \frac{1 - e^{-(s + 1)}}{s + 1} \] 2. The second integral: \[ e^{-1} \int_{0}^{1} e^{-st} \, dt = e^{-1} \left[ \frac{e^{-st}}{-s} \right]_{0}^{1} = e^{-1} \left( \frac{1 - e^{-s}}{s} \right) \] Combining these results, we get the Laplace transform \(X(s)\): \[ X(s) = \frac{1 - e^{-(s + 1)}}{s + 1} - \frac{e^{-1}(1 - e^{-s})}{s} \] Thus, the Laplace transform of the given signal is: \[ \boxed{\dfrac{1 - e^{-(s + 1)}}{s + 1} - \dfrac{e^{-1}(1 - e^{-s})}{s}} \]
